Text: What Teacher1 says about software development as a journey of different stages particularly rings true as our team gets closer to the finish line.
The last few weeks have certainly been the frustration phase, and luckily I think we are finally emerging from it onto the next one.

I hesitate to describe it as happy since we still have so much to do, but over the weekend everyone did some serious heavy-lifting and the application looked as though it has always been on the right track.
Gogo managed to have the PDF printing working, and it worked surprisingly well with our current setup.
I have almost finished binding data to the team and doctor views, while Bibi has finally nailed down how to stage pending updates and apply them in batch.
Of course, our code looks far from pretty, and there are some definitely corner-cuttings and duplicate codes that could do with some refactoring.
But still, I feel proud of it now that I know how much effort I have put into it.
I feel proud of my team as well as I know how much hours they've spent pouring over some weird WPF bugs, especially Bibi once you take a good look at our Git's commit log.
Susu meanwhile has been keeping track of user requirements and the academic portion as well, and she's already started on collecting artifacts and planning the presentation.
I guess the lesson drawn from this is that being in the struggle together really helps form a team despite our technical and personal differences.
Looking at the big picture, I feel quite fortunate to have experienced different conflicts in each project.
While project one was more on the client and project two was more on how to divide our tasks, this time it has fallen squarely on team dynamics rather than work ethics.
The biggest takeaway for me is just to accept and embrace people and projects because you don't really have any control over them anyway.
It's better to focus on how you can contribute and learn as much as I can along the way.
For this week, my goal as well as our team's goal is to finish the application as much as we can.
I feel like we are at 75% and we can pull off the remaining quarter with a few more late nights and early mornings.
